# Trivy findings accepted for this project, with the reasoning.
#
# Both entries below are properties a VPN gateway cannot function without.
# Silencing them here is deliberate and reviewed; it is not a blanket exclusion.
# Everything else is expected to pass, so a new finding fails the build.

# AWS-0104 — unrestricted egress from the security group.
# A VPN server forwards its clients' traffic to arbitrary internet
# destinations. That is the service. Restricting egress to a known set of
# addresses would mean the tunnel could only reach that set, which defeats the
# purpose of a full-tunnel VPN.
AWS-0104

# AWS-0164 — the subnet assigns public IP addresses on launch.
# Clients connect to this server from the public internet, so it must be
# publicly reachable. The exposure is controlled at the security group: a
# single UDP port for the tunnel, which is authenticated and encrypted, and
# SSH restricted to one address.
AWS-0164

# Not ignored, and deliberately left as a visible MEDIUM finding:
#   AWS-0178 — VPC flow logs are not enabled.
# Flow logs on a personal VPN would record metadata about the operator's own
# browsing, which works against the reason for running it, and they bill per
# ingested GB. Enable them if you need an audit trail and accept both.
